Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Chop the @sweet potato{2} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel).

Pop the wedges onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{a drizzle}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a medium #saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}. Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the #lid{}. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the #pan{} from the heat (still covered).

Leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, trim the @pak choi{1}(trimmed), then thinly slice widthways. Trim and halve the @green beans{80%g}(trimmed and halved).

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest and cut the @lime{1}(zested and cut into wedges) into wedges.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{240%g} and green beans. Stir-fry until the chicken is starting to brown, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Next, add the pak choi, garlic and the @Indonesian style spice mix{2%sachets}. Stir-fry for ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @peanut butter{30%g}, @ketjap manis{25%g}, @soy sauce{15%ml}, @sugar for the sauce{1%tsp} and @water for the sauce{100%ml}.

> The water and sugar amounts are for the sauce.

Bring to the boil, then simmer until the chicken is cooked through and the sauce is slightly thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir occasionally to break the peanut butter apart.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the sweet potato wedges have roasted, stir through the curry.

Stir in the lime zest and half of the lime juice.

Taste the curry and add more salt, pepper or more lime juice if needed.

Share the rice between #bowls{}. Spoon over your satay chicken curry.

Serve any remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over.

Enjoy!